# Architecture

## Governance

This rule is **priority 2** in the rule hierarchy. Supreme authority: `docs/architecture/ai-constitution.md`.

| Document | Path |
|----------|------|
| AI Constitution | `docs/architecture/ai-constitution.md` |
| Workflow (mandatory process) | `.cursor/rules/workflow.mdc` |
| Universal agent instructions | `AGENTS.md` |
| Project context skill (load first) | `.claude/skills/project-context/SKILL.md` |

Load `project-context` at session start. Never implement features without following `workflow.mdc`.

## Purpose

Enforce draft.io's **modular monolith** structure: a pnpm monorepo with a NestJS backend (`apps/backend`), Next.js frontend (`apps/frontend`), and shared packages (`packages/shared-types`). Each backend feature is a **bounded context** with strict layer boundaries. Dependency direction flows inward — domain at the center, infrastructure and presentation at the edges.

## Required Behavior

### Monorepo Layout

- **Apps** own runtime entry points; **packages** hold cross-cutting types and utilities only.
- Shared API contracts live in `@draft-io/shared-types` — never duplicate DTO shapes in frontend and backend.
- Run `pnpm architecture:check` after structural changes; dependency-cruiser rules in `.dependency-cruiser.cjs` are authoritative.

### Backend Module Structure

Every feature module under `apps/backend/src/modules/{name}/` follows four layers:

```
{module}/
├── application/     # use-cases, commands, queries
├── domain/          # entities, value-objects, errors, repository ports
├── infrastructure/  # Prisma repos, mappers, external adapters
├── presentation/    # controllers, DTOs, response mappers
└── {module}.module.ts
```

Reference implementation: `players/`. Copy this structure for new modules.

### Layer Dependency Rules

| Layer | May depend on | Must NOT depend on |
|-------|---------------|-------------------|
| Domain | `common/domain`, other modules' **value objects** only | infrastructure, application, presentation, NestJS, Prisma |
| Application | domain, commands/queries | infrastructure, presentation, NestJS, Prisma |
| Infrastructure | domain ports, Prisma, mappers | presentation |
| Presentation | application use cases, DTOs | infrastructure (except `*.module.ts` wiring) |

### Cross-Module Communication

- Reference other aggregates **by ID** (`playerIds: string[]`), never embed foreign entities in domain.
- Validate cross-module references in the **application layer** (e.g., verify player exists before assigning to team).
- Use domain events via `EventBus` for cross-module notifications (when implemented).

### Use Case Wiring

- Use cases are **plain TypeScript classes** — no `@Injectable`.
- Wire them with `provideUseCase()` in the module file.
- Repository ports use **injection tokens** (e.g., `PLAYER_REPOSITORY`).

## Forbidden Patterns

- Business logic in controllers, DTOs, or Prisma repositories.
- Importing another module's **entity** into your domain layer.
- Direct database joins across module boundaries.
- NestJS decorators (`@Injectable`, `@Controller`) in domain or application layers.
- Prisma client usage outside `infrastructure/`.
- Circular dependencies between modules.
- Leaking HTTP status codes or NestJS exceptions from domain errors.
- Creating microservices or shared "utils" modules that bypass bounded contexts.
- Importing `data-providers` from `players`/`teams`/`leagues` **domain** — use `core/external-reference/ExternalProvider` instead.
- Mapping API DTOs directly to domain entities — always go through `External*Record` and application mappers.

## Good Examples

```typescript
// application/use-cases/create-player.use-case.ts
export class CreatePlayerUseCase {
  constructor(private readonly playerRepository: PlayerRepository) {}

  async execute(command: CreatePlayerCommand): Promise<Player> {
    const player = Player.create({
      id: PlayerId.generate(uuidv4()),
      name: PlayerName.create(command.name),
      position: Position.create(command.position),
      overallRating: OverallRating.create(command.overallRating),
    });
    await this.playerRepository.save(player);
    return player;
  }
}
```

```typescript
// players.module.ts — infrastructure wired only here
@Module({
  controllers: [PlayersController],
  providers: [
    provideUseCase(CreatePlayerUseCase, [PLAYER_REPOSITORY]),
    { provide: PLAYER_REPOSITORY, useClass: PrismaPlayerRepository },
  ],
})
export class PlayersModule {}
```

```typescript
// Cross-module reference by ID only
export class Team extends Entity<TeamId> {
  private readonly _playerIds: readonly string[];
  private readonly _formationCode: string;
}
```

## Bad Examples

```typescript
// BAD: domain importing infrastructure
import { PrismaService } from '../../infrastructure/database/prisma.service';

export class Player extends Entity<PlayerId> {
  async save(prisma: PrismaService): Promise<void> {
    await prisma.player.create({ data: { ... } });
  }
}
```

```typescript
// BAD: controller with business logic
@Post()
async create(@Body() dto: CreatePlayerDto) {
  if (dto.overallRating > 99) throw new BadRequestException();
  return this.prisma.player.create({ data: dto });
}
```

```typescript
// BAD: embedding foreign aggregate in domain
import { Team } from '../../teams/domain/entities/team.entity';

export class League extends Entity<LeagueId> {
  private readonly _teams: Team[];
}
```

## Checklist

- [ ] `project-context` skill and `ai-constitution.md` consulted for this change
- [ ] `workflow.mdc` followed (plan before implement for major features)
- [ ] New code lives in the correct layer folder within its bounded context
- [ ] Domain and application layers have zero NestJS/Prisma imports
- [ ] Use cases are wired via `provideUseCase()` with repository tokens
- [ ] Cross-module references use IDs, validated in application layer
- [ ] API response shapes come from `@draft-io/shared-types`
- [ ] `pnpm architecture:check` passes with no violations
- [ ] Module follows `players/` as the reference template
